poem:
The Lay of Layover Bay  
Beware the glimmertide of Layover Bay, the shud-swoon swells;  
For flibberfang wakes in the duskdraft, his snarlsnare rings, clang-clang!  
All voyagers veil voices low, lest wifflewail wends through the dells;  
“Skreek! skreek!” the sky-sirens cry—turn timid hearts tang-tang.  

He packed the plunk-pack of pribble-bright gear; he buckled his bibble-band bold;  
He drank a draught of bramble-bright brew, burble-burb brave.  
“Beware the Glimmertide!” warned the crone; “Beware the fang-flash cold!”  
Yet on strode gallant Gallygosh, glint-gaunt but grave.  

He found the flibberfang, fog-flocked, where flickerflame ferns flare;  
“Fwoosh! fwoosh!” went the fire-flicked blade, flash-flick, flick-flack!  
The Glimmertide growled, gulp-grinned, but Gally’s glaive gashed the glare;  
“Zwing! zwing!” sang steel as the creature crumpled, crack-crack!  

Home he hied, hailed high with harps; the harbor hummed hurray!  
He danced through the dockside din, ding-dang, ding-dang!  
The crones croon now in Layover Bay, recounting the daring day;  
Yet ever the warning wind whispers: “Beware—clang-clang!”

The Awlward Ballad of Sniktsnag and Tharn
Beware ye the brindled brissle-snag with click-clack sniktsnag claw;
It whittles wicks from willow-wands while whee-whirr wails in maw—
The sniktsnag lurks by awlward stones, all jarnjag, glark and snarls;
When moon-murk murmurs, mark the mark; its thistle-threat unfurls!  

So gird ye, gallant gimlet-knight, with swivel-snath of steel;  
Grasp grip-grooved haft of hickory honed to hurl and heeel.  
With brindle-braced breastplate bright, your brawny-brisk heart thrums;  
Through bramble-bridge you brattle-bridge while clobber-clank drum-drum-drum!  

Snickety-snick! The sniktsnag snaps, its gimble-grin grows wide;  
You thrust through thrumming thornsnarl, a whirl-whirr awlward stride.  
Clangity-clang! Your steel-sung awl sinks snikt-snick into scale;  
The creature crumples, clatters, still—its click-clacks fail, frail, frail!  

Home hollers hoot-hoorah! with hurdy-hurrah hurdy-glees;  
They hoist you high on hoppet-stilts, they jamboree with jees;  
Fiddles fife and flagons froth, all frindle-frood and fun—  
Yet hush! the hushling hammers hum—still whispers warn the awl!

The Brownskittle Brawl

Beware the brown-burnt bisternook, my bairns, the butter-blink!
Its sizzle-snap bewrinkles dusk, its foam a frumptious frink;
It wurbles in the copper-kiln, it skrelches on the brink—
Take heed, take heed, O kitchen-keens, or lose your lunch to stink!

He brindled blades and brindlesticks, he clanged the clatter-cloome;
He salted stars and sugar-sands, he fetched the fragrant foom;
With whisk-whirr whapping whirlagig he stirred the sizzling gloom—
For none may quell the butter-blaze that stinks of sweet perfume.

One two! One two! The furnace blew! The foam in fizzing flight!
The Brownskittle—oh, skreek! skreek!—it leapt in gilded light;
With sporkle-spang and spatula-slam he flipped the foe from sight—
And brown-buttered the banquet-bowl in victor-vanquish rite.

Come hither, hearth-hugged heroes, come clap your clinky plates;
We’ll drizzle drams of drumbled gold where joy and savor mates;
We’ll gnash the night with nut-brown notes, with crackle-caramel fates—
And sing the skillet-slayer’s song through clanging castle gates.

Beware the brown-burnt bisternook, my bairns, the butter-blink!
Its sizzle-snap bewrinkles dusk, its foam a frumptious frink…

“Jamwock’s Throth-Bray”

1  
Beware the clikker-crank, my lad, the whirring wubber-strop,  
For snaggler-sprockets snarl the sheet where flibber-tongues do flop;  
The snickering Inkblight hides in hush, a shadow-shiver blob,  
And grumbling gears go glurk-glurk-glurk beneath the paper-mob.  

2  
With wizz-wand ready, whapper-shield, he braced the tray to pop;  
He tweaked the toggles, tapped the tabs, then primed the plucky hop;  
The drumbeats drummed like doodle-drops, the toners twanged a tune—  
All set to face the Jamwock, born of smudge and sullen moon.  

3  
One flicker-flash—there rose the beast! A jangle-jawed affront:  
Its snaggle-claws went scrick-scrack-scrick, its ribbon-tongue a runt.  
He dodged the clump-clump clawder-creep, his fingers fizzed and flew;  
Zip-zing! The page ripped free at last—thrrrip-rip!—the jam he slew!  

4  
He hauled the limp leaves high in glee, their edges crisp and clean;  
The office thrummed a thunder-cheer—“Our print-prince, swift and keen!”  
They danced a doodle-drum salute, confetti-carbon rained;  
The Jamwock lay in crumple-clump, its roar forever chained.  

5  
Beware the clikker-crank, my friend, lest smudges re-arise;  
Yet sing of valiant Vellum-Vance beneath these toner skies;  
For whenever printers growl and grind, the tale is told anew—  
“’Twas brillig, and the Jamwock snarled—till Vance its clatter slew!”
